1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
On June 22nd, 1986, in front of 114,000 screaming fans at the Azteca Stadium, one man did the impossible.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:13,200
He grabbed the ball in his own half — and ran. Past one defender. Then another. Then another.

3
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:18,267
Sixty yards, ten seconds, five defenders and a goalkeeper — all left behind.

4
00:00:18,267 --> 00:00:26,067
Four minutes earlier, that same man had cheated. He punched the ball into the net with his fist and got away with it.

5
00:00:26,067 --> 00:00:28,467
His name was Diego Armando Maradona.

6
00:00:28,467 --> 00:00:34,200
And this is the story of how the greatest footballer who ever lived destroyed himself.

7
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:42,000
Villa Fiorito. A shantytown on the edge of Buenos Aires, where the streets had no names and the houses had no floors.

8
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:45,400
This is where Diego was born on October 30th, 1960.

9
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:53,133
His father worked in a factory. His mother raised eight children in a house smaller than most people's living rooms.

10
00:00:53,133 --> 00:01:00,867
Diego got his first football at age three. And from the moment he touched it, everyone knew something was different.

11
00:01:00,867 --> 00:01:06,067
By eight years old, he was performing halftime tricks at professional matches.

12
00:01:06,067 --> 00:01:10,333
His youth team won 136 consecutive games. Without a single loss.

13
00:01:10,333 --> 00:01:16,933
At fourteen, he signed with Argentinos Juniors. At fifteen, training with grown men twice his size.

14
00:01:16,933 --> 00:01:21,867
On October 20th, 1976, Diego Armando Maradona made his professional debut.

15
00:01:21,867 --> 00:01:27,133
He was the youngest player to ever set foot on an Argentine professional pitch.

16
00:01:27,133 --> 00:01:30,200
But talent born in poverty comes with a price.

17
00:01:30,200 --> 00:01:36,000
The boy who had nothing suddenly had everything. And no one taught him how to carry it.

18
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:41,800
By twenty-one, Maradona had scored 115 goals for Argentinos Juniors.

19
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:48,367
Boca Juniors bought him, and he won the Argentine league in his first season.

20
00:01:48,367 --> 00:01:57,493
In 1982, FC Barcelona paid five million pounds — a world record — for a twenty-one-year-old from the slums.

21
00:01:57,493 --> 00:02:02,013
But Barcelona was a disaster. Hepatitis struck first.

22
00:02:02,013 --> 00:02:09,518
Then Goikoetxea shattered his ankle with a tackle so vicious it nearly ended his career.

23
00:02:09,518 --> 00:02:16,171
Thirty-eight goals in fifty-eight games — incredible numbers for a broken man.

24
00:02:16,171 --> 00:02:17,620
Then came Naples.

25
00:02:17,620 --> 00:02:25,808
On July 5th, 1984, Maradona arrived at Stadio San Paolo by helicopter. 75,000 fans were waiting.

26
00:02:25,808 --> 00:02:30,499
They chanted: Ho visto Maradona — I have seen Maradona.

27
00:02:30,499 --> 00:02:38,431
Naples was the poorest city in Italy. But Maradona gave them something they never had: pride.

28
00:02:38,431 --> 00:02:44,827
He won Napoli their first-ever Serie A title in 1987. Then another in 1990.

29
00:02:44,827 --> 00:02:49,348
He didn't just play for Naples — he became their god.

30
00:02:49,348 --> 00:02:56,000
They call him D10S — Dios, the Spanish word for God, fused with the number 10.

31
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:02,623
The 1986 World Cup in Mexico. This is where Diego Maradona became immortal.

32
00:03:02,623 --> 00:03:10,835
Argentina had been knocked out early in 1982. The country was reeling from the Falklands War.

33
00:03:10,835 --> 00:03:19,577
When the two nations met in the quarter-finals, it wasn't just football. It was war by other means.

34
00:03:19,577 --> 00:03:22,756
The score was zero-zero at halftime.

35
00:03:22,756 --> 00:03:30,791
Then, in the fifty-first minute, the ball deflected into the air off England's Steve Hodge.

36
00:03:30,791 --> 00:03:38,738
Maradona and Shilton both jumped. Shilton was taller. But Maradona's fist got there first.

37
00:03:38,738 --> 00:03:44,037
He punched the ball into the net. The referee didn't see it.

38
00:03:44,037 --> 00:03:50,218
A little with the head of Maradona, and a little with the hand of God.

39
00:03:50,218 --> 00:03:56,575
But what happened four minutes later made the world forget the cheating.

40
00:03:56,575 --> 00:04:02,403
Maradona receives the ball in his own half. He turns. And he runs.

41
00:04:02,403 --> 00:04:07,702
Past Beardsley. Past Reid. Fenwick lunges — nothing but air.

42
00:04:07,702 --> 00:04:15,737
Butcher closes in. Maradona goes around him. Butcher tries again. Around him a second time.

43
00:04:15,737 --> 00:04:24,744
Just him and Shilton. The goalkeeper spreads wide. Maradona drags the ball past him into an empty net.

44
00:04:24,744 --> 00:04:29,689
Sixty yards. Ten seconds. The greatest goal ever scored.

45
00:04:29,689 --> 00:04:38,431
In the final, 2-2 with six minutes to go. Maradona threaded the pass. Burruchaga scored the winner.

46
00:04:38,431 --> 00:04:41,168
Argentina were world champions.

47
00:04:41,168 --> 00:04:46,555
Five goals, five assists — ten of Argentina's fourteen goals.

48
00:04:46,555 --> 00:04:53,354
Ninety dribbles. Fouled fifty-three times. The Golden Ball by unanimous vote.

49
00:04:53,354 --> 00:04:59,800
The single greatest individual performance in the history of team sports.

50
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:05,128
The god had a demon. And the demon's name was cocaine.

51
00:05:05,128 --> 00:05:11,540
In Naples, the parties never stopped. The Camorra surrounded him.

52
00:05:11,540 --> 00:05:16,868
The women. The drugs. The lifestyle of a living deity.

53
00:05:16,868 --> 00:05:23,379
On March 17th, 1991, cocaine in his system. Fifteen months banned.

54
00:05:23,379 --> 00:05:29,200
The city that worshipped him watched him leave in disgrace.

55
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:35,909
He went to Sevilla. Then back to Argentina. The drugs never stopped.

56
00:05:35,909 --> 00:05:43,604
In 1994, he returned to the World Cup. Thirty-three. Overweight. Out of shape.

57
00:05:43,604 --> 00:05:51,201
Against Greece, he scored and ran to the camera, screaming with bulging eyes.

58
00:05:51,201 --> 00:05:58,304
It was terrifying. It was electric. The last great moment of his career.

59
00:05:58,304 --> 00:06:04,914
Four days later, positive for five variants of ephedrine. Expelled.

60
00:06:04,914 --> 00:06:11,327
His World Cup was over. His career at the highest level was over.

61
00:06:11,327 --> 00:06:13,300
No one believed him.

62
00:06:13,300 --> 00:06:21,273
After retirement, the man who could do anything with a football could do nothing without one.

63
00:06:21,273 --> 00:06:27,788
His weight ballooned to 280 pounds. In 2000, a cocaine-induced heart attack.

64
00:06:27,788 --> 00:06:32,075
In 2004, another. In 2005, gastric bypass surgery.

65
00:06:32,075 --> 00:06:37,390
He tried coaching. Argentina — eliminated by Germany four-nil.

66
00:06:37,390 --> 00:06:43,734
His final post was at Gimnasia. He was still their coach when it happened.

67
00:06:43,734 --> 00:06:49,992
November 25th, 2020. Cardiac arrest in his sleep. He was sixty years old.

68
00:06:49,992 --> 00:06:58,050
Hundreds of thousands lined the streets of Buenos Aires, in a global pandemic, to say goodbye.

69
00:06:58,050 --> 00:07:02,080
His heart weighed nearly twice the normal size.

70
00:07:02,080 --> 00:07:08,681
Eight members of his medical staff are standing trial for negligent homicide.

71
00:07:08,681 --> 00:07:14,339
Diego Maradona was born with nothing in a shantytown with no name.

72
00:07:14,339 --> 00:07:19,311
He became the greatest footballer the world has ever seen.

73
00:07:19,311 --> 00:07:28,055
He was worshipped as a god. And he destroyed himself with the same hands that once touched the divine.

74
00:07:28,055 --> 00:07:32,942
He was not a perfect man. But he played perfect football.

75
00:07:32,942 --> 00:07:39,200
And for those who saw him — truly saw him — nothing else ever came close.
